<subSubSection id="49C942EEFF9B3943EBD2C6EDFABC58A7" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="016C1165FF9B3943EBD2C6EDFEAA5ACE" blockId="53.[227,341,478,504]" box="[227,341,478,504]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">
<heading id="5A24A609FF9B3943EBD2C6EDFEAA5ACE" bold="true" box="[227,341,478,504]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" reason="3">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF9B3943EBD2C6EDFEAA5ACE" bold="true" box="[227,341,478,504]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="016C1165FF9B3943EBD2C53EFABC58A7" blockId="53.[225,1438,525,913]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">
The otoliths of this new species are somewhat similar looking to those of the co-occurring 
<taxonomicName id="C6D36AE6FF9B3943EFCCC53EFD64597A" authority="(Dante &amp; Frizzell, 1965)" baseAuthorityName="Dante &amp; Frizzell" baseAuthorityYear="1965" class="Actinopterygii" family="Ophidiidae" genus="Hoplobrotula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophidiiformes" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="melrosensis">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF9B3943EFCCC53EFE93597D" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Hoplobrotula melrosensis</emphasis>
(Dante &amp; 
<bibRefCitation id="65426C94FF9B3943EADCC502FD6C597A" author="Frizzell D. L." box="[493,659,561,588]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" pagination="85 - 110" refId="ref53928" refString="Frizzell D. L. 1965. Otolith-based genera and lineages of fossil bonefishes (Clupeiformes, Albulidae). Senckenbergiana Lethaea 46 a: 85 - 110." type="book chapter" year="1965">Frizzell, 1965</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and also to those of 
<taxonomicName id="C6D36AE6FF9B3943E8A8C501FAC9597D" authority="(Koken, 1888)" baseAuthorityName="Koken" baseAuthorityYear="1888" box="[921,1334,561,587]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Ophidiidae" genus="Bauzaia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophidiiformes" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mucronata">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF9B3943E8A8C501FB80597D" box="[921,1151,562,587]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Bauzaia mucronata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="65426C94FF9B3943EFBEC502FAD2597D" author="Koken" box="[1167,1325,561,587]" firstAuthor="Koken" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" pagination="274 - 305" refId="ref54599" refString="Koken E. 1888. Neue Untersuchungen an tertiaren Fisch-Otolithen. Zeitschrift der deutschen geologischen Gesellschaft 40: 274 - 305." type="journal article" year="1888">Koken, 1888</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, but this similarity is only superficial and restricted to the outline of the otoliths. Firstly, the sulcus of both 
<taxonomicName id="C6D36AE6FF9B3943EBD2C549FE6B59A2" baseAuthorityName="Dante &amp; Frizzell" baseAuthorityYear="1965" box="[227,404,634,660]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Ophidiidae" genus="Hoplobrotula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophidiiformes" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="melrosensis">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF9B3943EBD2C549FE6B59A2" box="[227,404,634,660]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">H. melrosensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="C6D36AE6FF9B3943EAE4C549FD8859A5" baseAuthorityName="Koken" baseAuthorityYear="1888" box="[469,631,634,659]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Ophidiidae" genus="Bauzaia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophidiiformes" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mucronata">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF9B3943EAE4C549FD8859A5" box="[469,631,634,659]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">B. mucronata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are clearly divided into an ostium and cauda, and secondly, their posterior end is much more extended and spine-like. The sulcus of “aff. 
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF9B3943EF17C5ADFBC4598E" box="[1062,1083,670,696]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">G</emphasis>
.” 
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF9B3943EF66C5ACFB43598E" box="[1111,1212,671,696]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">stringeri</emphasis>
sp. nov. is straight, and the posterior tip is located in their lower part. Although the posterior part of the otoliths resembles that of the extant genus 
<taxonomicName id="C6D36AE6FF9B3943E938C5D5FD465836" authorityName="Alcock" authorityYear="1889" box="[521,697,742,768]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Ophidiidae" genus="Glyptophidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophidiiformes" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF9B3943E938C5D5FD465836" box="[521,697,742,768]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Glyptophidium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, this genus has a sulcus 
<typeStatus id="DE68AFC7FF9B3943E8D9C5D4FBE45837" box="[1000,1051,743,769]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">type</typeStatus>
with distinct ostium and cauda. The lack of a clear division between ostium and cauda in the sulcus of “aff. 
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF9B3943EFA8C438FB515813" box="[1177,1198,779,805]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">G</emphasis>
.” 
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF9B3943EFFFC438FACC5812" box="[1230,1331,779,804]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">stringeri</emphasis>
sp. nov. suggests affinities to 
<taxonomicName id="C6D36AE6FF9B3943EAEAC41DFD74587E" authorityName="Alcock" authorityYear="1889" box="[475,651,814,840]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Ophidiidae" genus="Glyptophidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophidiiformes" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF9B3943EAEAC41DFD74587E" box="[475,651,814,840]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Glyptophidium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but does not imply a certain attribution to that genus. Two related Eocene species with similar features are “aff. 
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF9B3943E9C1C460FCFA585B" box="[752,773,851,877]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">G</emphasis>
.” 
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF9B3943E810C460FC52585B" box="[801,941,851,877]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">biarritzense</emphasis>
(Sulc, 1932) from the 
<collectingRegion id="C317DF87FF9B3943EF81C460FADB585B" box="[1200,1316,851,877]" country="France" name="Aquitaine" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Aquitaine</collectingRegion>
Basin and “aff. 
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF9B3943EA2FC444FECC58A7" box="[286,307,887,913]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">G</emphasis>
.” 
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF9B3943EA7EC444FDD158A7" box="[335,558,887,913]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">pseudobiarritzense</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="65426C94FF9B3943E907C444FCD858A7" author="Nolf &amp; Bajpai" box="[566,807,887,913]" firstAuthor="Nolf" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" pagination="195 - 221" refId="ref55941" refString="Nolf D. &amp; Bajpai S. 1992. Marine middle Eocene fish otoliths from India and Java. Bulletin de l'Institut royal des Sciences naturelles de Belgique, Sciences de la Terre 62: 195 - 221." type="journal article" year="1992">Nolf &amp; Bajpai, 1992</bibRefCitation>
from Java (
<bibRefCitation id="65426C94FF9B3943E883C444FB5D58A7" author="Nolf &amp; Bajpai" box="[946,1186,887,913]" firstAuthor="Nolf" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" pagination="195 - 221" refId="ref55941" refString="Nolf D. &amp; Bajpai S. 1992. Marine middle Eocene fish otoliths from India and Java. Bulletin de l'Institut royal des Sciences naturelles de Belgique, Sciences de la Terre 62: 195 - 221." type="journal article" year="1992">Nolf &amp; Bajpai 1992</bibRefCitation>
: pl. 3 fig. 11).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
